{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772048168,"nonce":"sR/9V4lFpAdUwayaQ54KxKx/Ajk=","title":"Support adaptive-length trials (variable episode length)","message":"[Imported from GitHub #37] (created 2026-01-25T23:29:31Z)\n\n## Motivation\n\nIn some scenarios, it would be valuable for trials to end when a condition is met (e.g., reaching the target) rather than running for a fixed number of steps. This is common in RL and could enable:\n\n- More efficient training (don't waste compute on already-completed trials)\n- More realistic task structure (real reaches end when you arrive)\n- Curriculum learning based on trial duration\n\n## Challenges\n\n1. **JAX compilation**: `lax.scan` and `lax.fori_loop` expect static iteration counts for shape inference. Dynamic iteration requires `lax.while_loop`, which has different semantics.\n\n2. **Batching/parallelization**: Variable-length trials in a batch require masking or padding, which adds complexity:\n   - Masked loss computation\n   - Handling different termination times across batch\n   - Memory layout issues\n\n3. **State history**: If trials have different lengths, state trajectories have different shapes across batch. Requires ragged arrays or padding.\n\n4. **Loss computation**: Need to handle variable-length sequences, potentially with different discount schemes per trial.\n\n## Possible Approaches\n\n1. **Maximum length + early termination mask**: Run all trials for max length, but mask out post-termination steps. Simple but wasteful.\n\n2. **Bucketed batching**: Group trials by similar length. Reduces waste but adds complexity.\n\n3. **Per-trial compilation**: Compile separately for each trial length. Expensive but exact.\n\n4. **`lax.while_loop`**: True dynamic iteration, but can't easily batch and has JIT constraints.\n\n## Current Status\n\nFor now, feedbax uses fixed-length trials (`n_steps` as a field on Task). This is sufficient for most neuroscience experiments where trial structure is controlled.\n\nVariable-length support is deferred but the architecture (explicit Graph with cycle detection) doesn't preclude it - the iteration logic would need to change, but not the graph structure.\n\n---\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.5 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}